'''Brumalia''' ({{lang-la|Brumalia}}, {{IPA-la|bruːˈmaːlɪ.a|}}, "winter festivals")  was an [[ancient Roman]], [[winter solstice]] [[festival]] honouring [[Saturn (mythology)|Saturn]]/[[Cronus]] and [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]]/[[Demeter]], and [[Bacchus]] in some cases. By the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine era]], celebrations commenced on 24 November and lasted for a month, until [[Saturnalia]] and the "Waxing of the Light". The festival included night-time feasting, drinking, and merriment. During this time, prophetic indications were taken as prospects for the remainder of the winter. The festival was celebrated as late as the 6th century, until emperor [[Justinian]]'s [[Justinian I#Suppression of religions|repression of paganism]].{{sfn|Mazza|2011|pp=172-193}}{{sfn|John the Lydian|2009}}{{sfn|Crawford|1914}}

==Etymology==
The name of Brumalia comes from {{lang|la|[[wikt:bruma#Latin|brvma]]}}, {{IPA-la|ˈbruːma|}}, "Winter solstice", "Winter cold"; a shortening of {{lang|la|[[wikt:brevis#Latin|*brevima]]}}, {{IPA-la|ˈbrɛwɪma|}}, presumed obsolete superlative form of {{smallcaps|''[[wikt:brevis#Latin|brevis]]''}}, later {{lang|la|[[wikt:brevissimus#Latin|brevissima]]}} ("smallest", "shallowest", "briefest").

==Overview==
Roman life, during [[classical antiquity]], centred on the [[Roman army|military]], [[Roman agriculture|agriculture]], and hunting. The short, cold days of [[winter]] would halt most forms of work. Brumalia was a festival celebrated during this ''dark'', interludal period. It was [[chthonic]] in character and associated with [[crops]], of which seeds are [[sown]] in the ground before sprouting.{{sfn|John the Lydian|2009}}

Farmers would [[animal sacrifice|sacrifice]] pigs to Saturn and Ceres. [[viticulture|Vine-growers]] would sacrifice goats in honor of [[Bacchus]]—for the goat is an enemy of the vine; and they would skin them, fill the skin-bags with air and jump on them. Civic officials would bring offerings of [[firstfruits]] (including wine, olive oil, grain, and honey) to the priests of Ceres.{{sfn|John the Lydian|2009}}

Although Brumalia was still celebrated as late as the 6th century, it was uncommon and celebrants were ostracised by the Christian church. However, some practices did persist as November and December time customs.{{sfn|John the Lydian|2009}}

In later times, Romans would greet each other with words of blessing at night, "{{lang|la|Vives annos}}", "Live for years".{{sfn|John the Lydian|2009}}

==Contemporary celebration==
{{citation needed span|text=It is also revived as a festival annually held by [[Connecticut College]].|date=March 2013}}

