{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox animanga/Header | name = Eroica - The Glory of Napoleon | image = Eikou no Napoleon Eroica.jpg | image_size = 170px | caption = Cover of the first book. | ja_kanji = 栄光のナポレオン – エロイカ | ja_romaji = Eikou no Naporeon – Eroika | genre = Historical, Drama }} {{Infobox animanga/Print | type = manga | author = [[Riyoko Ikeda]] | publisher = [[Chuoukouronsha]] | demographic = ''[[Shōjo manga|Shōjo]]'' | magazine = | first = 1986 | last = 1995 | volumes = 12 | volume_list = }} {{Infobox animanga/Footer}}
{{nihongo|'''''Eroica - The Glory of Napoleon'''''|栄光のナポレオン – エロイカ|Eikō no Naporeon - Eroika}} is a [[manga]] by [[Riyoko Ikeda]] that is a [[sequel]] to ''[[The Rose of Versailles]]''.
It tells the story of [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]]'s empire, including the [[Thermidorian Reaction]], the [[French Revolutionary Wars: Campaigns of 1796#Italy|Italian Campaign]], the [[French Invasion of Egypt (1798)|Egyptian Campaign]], the [[Battle of the Nile]], the coup of [[18 Brumaire]], and the [[French invasion of Russia]].
It also includes some characters from the manga ''The Rose of Versailles'', like [[Alain de Soissons]], [[Bernard Chatelet]], and [[Rosalie (Lady Oscar)|Rosalie Lamorlière]].
== Characters == === Real Characters === * [[Napoleon Bonaparte]]: the main [[protagonist]] of the series. He was briefly appeared before in the manga ''The Rose of Versailles'', but not in the anime version. * [[Joséphine de Beauharnais]]: the female protagonist of the series. * [[Marie Louise, Duchess of Parma|Marie Louise of Austria]] * [[Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord]] * [[Joseph Fouché]] * [[Désirée Clary]] * [[Eugène de Beauharnais]] * [[Hortense de Beauharnais]] * [[Joseph Bonaparte]]: one of Napoleon's older brothers. * [[Pauline Bonaparte]] * [[Joachim Murat]] * [[François-Paul Brueys d'Aigalliers]] * [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]] * [[Alexander I of Russia]]: the main [[antagonist]] in the last part of the series. * [[Prince Klemens Wenzel von Metternich]] * [[William Pitt the Younger]] * [[Marie Walewska]] * [[Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson]] * [[Mikhail Illarionovich Kutuzov]] * [[Carl von Clausewitz]] * [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]] * [[Józef Antoni Poniatowski]]: Riyoko Ikeda wrote his story as ''[[Ten no Hate Made]]'' in 1990. The later part of the story is written almost same as a part of ''Eroica'' but from aspect of Poniatowski. * [[Murad Bey]]
=== Fictional Characters === {{see also|List of The Rose of Versailles characters}} * Alain de Soissons (1760–1804): a character from ''The Rose of Versailles'', was the sergeant of the Company B, the troops assigned to Lady Oscar's service in the National Guard. He accepted Oscar at first, and even befriended André and smuggled him in the troops, but after learning the truth about her he violently rejected her leadership. Oscar had to fight him to win he and the group's respect back, since they refused to be ordered around by a noble. After losing to Oscar and begging her to save the life of a companion who was about to be executed, which she did, he forgave Oscar and became fiercely devoted to her, even falling in love with her in the manga; still, he knew he couldn't fight against her feelings for André. Ultimately, he survives the French Revolution and the Terror, leading a quiet life in the country. He also appears in ''Eroica'' and is the coprotagonist in the first part of this story. * Bernard Chatelet (1760–1804): a returning character from ''The Rose of Versailles''. * Rosalie Chatelet (née Lamorlière): a returning character from ''The Rose of Versailles'', was [[Rosalie Lamorlière|a real person]], although her life and marriage were much fictionalized. Since ''The Rose of Versailles'', she has gotten married to Bernard Chatelet and had a son, Francois. * François Chatelet: the only son of Bernard and Rosalie, born in 1789. * Catherine Renaudin (Madame de Talleyrand): the main antagonist in the first part of the story. Catherine is the new [[love interest]] of Alain, but she is deeply royalist. * [[Oscar François de Jarjayes]] (1755–1789): although she had died during ''The Rose of Versailles'', is often seen only in [[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]] in the first part of this story.
